8.1 K-Means Clustering¶

n_clusters is the number of clusters to form as well as the number of centroids to generate.

n_init is the number of time the k-means algorithm will be run with different centroid seeds. The final results will be the best output of n_init consecutive runs in terms of inertia. Inertia is the sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center.

Here we compare using n_init=1 to n_init=50. We attempt to minimize the inertia/total within-cluster sum of squares.

In [ ]:
# K = 2
km1 = KMeans(n_clusters = 2, n_init = 1, random_state = 1)
km1.fit(X)

# Inertia
km1.inertia_
Out[ ]:
191.21018307993666
In [ ]:
# K = 2
km1 = KMeans(n_clusters = 2, n_init = 50, random_state = 1)
km1.fit(X)

km1.inertia_
Out[ ]:
187.9631538329325

We strongly recommend running K-means clustering with a large value of n_init, such as 20 or 50. Otherwise, an undesirable local optimum may be obtained.

8.2 Hierarchical Clustering¶

Use Euclidean distance as the dissimilarity measure.

In [ ]:
clustering_complete = AgglomerativeClustering(linkage='complete').fit(X) 
clustering_average = AgglomerativeClustering(linkage='average').fit(X)
clustering_single = AgglomerativeClustering(linkage='single').fit(X)
In [ ]:
fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(3, 1, figsize = (7,15))

ax1.scatter(X[:,0], X[:,1], s = 50, c = clustering_complete.labels_, cmap = 'viridis') 
ax1.set_title('Complete linkage')

ax2.scatter(X[:,0], X[:,1], s = 50, c = clustering_average.labels_, cmap = 'viridis') 
ax2.set_title('Average linkage')

ax3.scatter(X[:,0], X[:,1], s = 50, c = clustering_single.labels_, cmap = 'viridis') 
ax3.set_title('Single linkage')
Out[ ]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Single linkage')

Single linkage separates the observations into their correct groups.

Now we can plot the hierarchical clustering as a dendrogram. To scale the variables before performing hierarchical clustering of the observations, we use scale() function from sklearn.preprocessing.

In [ ]:
clustering_complete = hierarchy.complete(scale(X))
clustering_average = hierarchy.average(scale(X))
clustering_single = hierarchy.single(scale(X))
In [ ]:
fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(3, 1, figsize = (15,18))
for linkage, ax in zip([clustering_complete, clustering_average, clustering_single], [ax1, ax2, ax3]):
    cluster = hierarchy.dendrogram(linkage, ax = ax, color_threshold = 0)

ax1.set_title('Complete Linkage')
ax2.set_title('Average Linkage')
ax3.set_title('Single Linkage');

Use the correlation-based distance as the dissimilarity measure.

First, we need to calculate the correlation-based distance. This only makes sense for data with at least three features since the absolute correlation between any two observations with measurements on two features is always 1. Hence we will generate a three-dimensional dataset.

Similar shape corresponds to the correlation closer to $1$, hence we consider $1 -$ correlation as the dissimilarity measure. The closer to $0$ this value is, the more similarity we have.

In [ ]:
np.random.seed(1)
x = np.random.standard_normal((30,3))
df = pd.DataFrame(x)
corr = pairwise_distances(df, metric = "correlation")
In [ ]:
clustering_complete = hierarchy.complete(corr)
hierarchy.dendrogram(clustering_complete, color_threshold = 0)
plt.show()

8.3 Spectral Clustering¶

Implement spectral clustering using a radial basis function (RBF) kernel. Please play with SpectralClustering with different input parameters. You will be required to implement different spectral clustering methods via simulations in this week's assessment.

In [ ]:
spectral1 = SpectralClustering(n_clusters = 2, n_init=50, affinity='rbf', gamma=4.5, random_state=1).fit(X)
plt.scatter(X[:,0], X[:,1], s = 50, c=spectral1.labels_, cmap='viridis') 
plt.title('Spectral Clustering')
